{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 10:07:21.370087", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos EBGP lab\nPrepared: now\n\n1) Executive summary\n- Overall BGP control plane is mostly healthy except for a single problematic adjacency: the BGP session between spine_router_0_1 (172.16.0.3, AS 65101) and leaf_router_0_1 (172.16.0.11, AS 65201) is not reaching Established. All other BGP sessions in the fabric are up and exchanging routes.\n- The failing adjacency exhibits signs of a connection-collision / BGP NOTIFICATION (Cease - Connection Collision Resolution). TCP between the two devices is established but BGP remains stuck (one side OpenSent, the other in Idle/notification loop).\n- Fault is localized to the pair: spine_router_0_1 <-> leaf_router_0_1. Root cause is BGP connection collision / notification behavior preventing session negotiation completion (details below).\n- Impact: loss of that single spine–leaf adjacency reduces path diversity but other adjacencies remain up, so full reachability appears preserved via alternate paths. (I only report observations; no remediation is proposed here.)\n\n2) Health: overall view\n- All devices are up and IP interfaces are configured.\n- BGP sessions:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 ↔ spine_router_0_0: Established (healthy).\n  - leaf_router_0_0 ↔ spine_router_0_1: Established (healthy).\n  - leaf_router_0_1 ↔ spine_router_0_0: Established (healthy).\n  - leaf_router_0_1 ↔ spine_router_0_1: NOT established (problem).\n  - spine_router_0_0 ↔ super_spine_router_0: Established (healthy).\n  - spine_router_0_1 ↔ super_spine_router_0: Established (healthy).\n\n3) Abnormal behavior detected\n- Asymmetric BGP state between the two peers:\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (local AS 65201) reports neighbor 172.16.0.10 (spine_router_0_1) in state OpenSent (it has sent an OPEN but not completed the handshake).\n    - Evidence (leaf_router_0_1 show ip bgp summary): neighbor 172.16.0.10 ... State/PfxRcd: \"never  OpenSent\"\n    - Neighbor detail (leaf_router_0_1 show ip bgp neighbors 172.16.0.10): \"BGP state = OpenSent\" and \"Opens: Sent 1  Rcvd 0\" and \"Waiting for peer OPEN\".\n  - spine_router_0_1 (local AS 65101) reports neighbor 172.16.0.11 in state Idle and shows repeated Notifications and Opens, with last reset due to \"Notification sent (Cease/Connection Collision Resolution)\".\n    - Evidence (spine_router_0_1 show ip bgp neighbors 172.16.0.11): \"BGP state = Idle\", \"Opens: Sent 6 Rcvd 6\", \"Notifications: Sent 6 Rcvd 0\", \"Notification sent (Cease/Connection Collision Resolution)\". A hex dump in the output contains ASCII for the neighbor hostname (confirming message content seen).\n- TCP-level: netstat on both sides shows an ESTABLISHED TCP connection between 172.16.0.10:179 (spine) and 172.16.0.11:<ephemeral port> (leaf). So TCP is established, but BGP finite-state machine is repeatedly failing to progress to Established.\n  - Evidence (netstat outputs): both hosts show ESTABLISHED entries for the peer IPs and port 179.\n\n4) Localization (faulty devices / adjacency)\n- Primary affected adjacency: spine_router_0_1 (172.16.0.10) <-> leaf_router_0_1 (172.16.0.11).\n- Other routers (leaf_router_0_0, spine_router_0_0, super_spine_router_0) show normal BGP sessions and expected routes; they are not implicated in this specific failure.\n\n5) Relevant configuration & routing facts (observed)\n- leaf_router_0_1 config:\n  - router bgp 65201\n  - neighbors: 172.16.0.6 remote-as 65100, 172.16.0.10 remote-as 65101\n  - network advertised: 10.0.1.0/24\n- spine_router_0_1 config:\n  - router bgp 65101\n  - neighbors: 172.16.0.2 remote-as 65000, 172.16.0.9 remote-as 65200, 172.16.0.11 remote-as 65201\n- IP addressing on the leaf/spine interconnect:\n  - spine_router_0_1 eth2 = 172.16.0.10/31\n  - leaf_router_0_1 eth1 = 172.16.0.11/31\n- Routing tables show other legs of the Clos have learned prefixes (10.0.0.0/24, 10.0.1.0/24) via BGP on different neighbors — indicating route propagation via alternate spines exists.\n\n6) Root-cause analysis (most likely)\n- The BGP session between spine_router_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 fails to progress due to connection-collision behavior: both sides attempt to form BGP TCP connections around the same time, BGP collision resolution is triggered and a NOTIFICATION (Cease: Connection Collision Resolution) is being sent by spine_router_0_1. The result is a persistent state where spine_router_0_1 cycles to Idle (with notifications) while leaf_router_0_1 remains in OpenSent waiting for a peer OPEN.\n- Supporting clues:\n  - The spine shows explicit Notification sent: \"Cease/Connection Collision Resolution\".\n  - The leaf is stuck in OpenSent and reports it has sent an OPEN but not received a peer OPEN.\n  - Netstat shows TCP is established (so the TCP handshake completes) but the BGP state machine on one or both sides is not transiting to Established — consistent with BGP-level NOTIFICATION and session teardown occurring after TCP setup.\n  - The hex dump in the spine's neighbor detail includes the neighbor hostname, indicating spine received a BGP OPEN from the leaf and then generated a Notification.\n- Possible contributing factors (observed but not proven): simultaneous connection attempts, connection sharing issues on a shared network, or a mismatch in some BGP session negotiation parameter/capability causing one side to send a NOTIFICATION on receipt of the other's OPEN. The configuration shows AS numbers and neighbor statements appear correct on both sides; no obvious AS mismatch is visible in the static configs collected.\n\n7) Observed impact\n- The single failed adjacency reduces topology redundancy (one spine–leaf link not carrying BGP adjacencies), but other adjacencies are up. Routing tables on the devices still show learned prefixes for both host subnets (via alternate paths), so full host-to-host reachability likely remains functional via alternate spine(s). However, the failed adjacency is a control-plane anomaly that should be investigated further (beyond this report) because it reduces resilience.\n\n8) Evidence excerpts (key outputs)\n- leaf_router_0_1 show ip bgp summary:\n  - neighbor 172.16.0.10 ... State: OpenSent\n- leaf_router_0_1 neighbor detail (172.16.0.10):\n  - \"BGP state = OpenSent\", \"Opens: Sent 1 Rcvd 0\", \"Waiting for peer OPEN\"\n- spine_router_0_1 show ip bgp neighbors 172.16.0.11:\n  - \"BGP state = Idle\", \"Opens: Sent 6 Rcvd 6\", \"Notifications: Sent 6 Rcvd 0\", \"Notification sent (Cease/Connection Collision Resolution)\"\n- netstat on both endpoints shows ESTABLISHED TCP connection between 172.16.0.10:179 and 172.16.0.11:<ephemeral>.\n- Other BGP summaries show peers with State/PfxRcd populated (i.e., established) e.g. spine_router_0_0 and super-spine sessions are up.\n\n9) Conclusion (diagnostic)\n- An anomaly is present: the BGP adjacency spine_router_0_1 ↔ leaf_router_0_1 is failing to reach Established due to BGP-level connection-collision / NOTIFICATION Cease behavior. The problem is localized to that adjacency (both endpoint routers are implicated). The most plausible root cause is simultaneous connection attempts leading to collision resolution and subsequent BGP NOTIFICATION behavior (or an OPEN-capability mismatch that triggers a NOTIFICATION on receipt of the peer OPEN). Other fabric BGP sessions are healthy and the network has alternate paths, but the failed adjacency reduces redundancy.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- collect more diagnostic logs/messages (BGP debug logs, exact NOTIFICATION code/payload decoded), or\n- run additional targeted tests (repeated neighbor detail, tcpdump on the interface to capture the BGP OPEN/NOTIFICATION exchange) to definitively identify which side is generating the Notification and the precise reason code/payload. (This is optional — say if you want more evidence.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 15195, 